{"parse":{"title":"Mihira Bhoja","pageid":2341023,"revid":856604063,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p class=\"mw-empty-elt\"> \n</p>\n<div role=\"note\" class=\"hatnote navigation-not-searchable\">Not to be confused with <a href=\"/wiki/Bhoja\" title=\"Bhoja\">Bhoja</a>.</div>\n<p class=\"mw-empty-elt\">\n\n</p>\n<table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" class=\"fn\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold;background-color: #cbe; font-size: 125%\">Mihira Bhoja</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<i>Adivaraha</i> <small></small></td></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" class=\"photo\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Statue_of_Gurjar_Samraat_Mihir_Bhoj_Mahaan_in_Bharat_Upvan_ofAkshardham_Mandir_New_Delhi.jpg\" class=\"image\" title=\"Mihira Bhoja\"><img alt=\"Mihira Bhoja\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8b/Statue_of_Gurjar_Samraat_Mihir_Bhoj_Mahaan_in_Bharat_Upvan_ofAkshardham_Mandir_New_Delhi.jpg/220px-Statue_of_Gurjar_Samraat_Mihir_Bhoj_Mahaan_in_Bharat_Upvan_ofAkshardham_Mandir_New_Delhi.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"369\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/8/8b/Statue_of_Gurjar_Samraat_Mihir_Bhoj_Mahaan_in_Bharat_Upvan_ofAkshardham_Mandir_New_Delhi.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"228\" data-file-height=\"382\" /></a><div>A 21st century statue of Mihira Bhoja in Delhi</div></td></tr><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;background-color: #e4dcf6\">6th <a href=\"/wiki/Gurjara-Pratihara\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gurjara-Pratihara\">Gurjara-Pratihara</a> king</th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Reign</th><td>\n<abbr title=\"circa\">c.</abbr><span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#8201;836</span>&#160;\u2013 c.<span style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#8201;885 CE</span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Predecessor</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Ramabhadra\" title=\"Ramabhadra\">Ramabhadra</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Successor</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Mahendrapala_I\" title=\"Mahendrapala I\">Mahendrapala I</a></td></tr><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;background-color: #e4dcf6\"><div style=\"height: 4px; width:100%;\"></div></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>\n885<br /><a href=\"/wiki/Narmada_River\" title=\"Narmada River\">Narmada River</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Issue</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Mahendrapala_I\" title=\"Mahendrapala I\">Mahendrapala I</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Father</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Ramabhadra\" title=\"Ramabhadra\">Ramabhadra</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Religion</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Hinduism\" title=\"Hinduism\">Hinduism</a><sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2016)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Mihira Bhoja</b> (836\u2013885 CE) or <b>Bhoja I</b> was a ruler of the <a href=\"/wiki/Gurjara-Pratihara\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gurjara-Pratihara\">Gurjara-Pratihara</a> dynasty of <a href=\"/wiki/India\" title=\"India\">India</a>. He succeeded his father <a href=\"/wiki/Ramabhadra\" title=\"Ramabhadra\">Ramabhadra</a>. Bhoja was a devotee of <a href=\"/wiki/Vishnu\" title=\"Vishnu\">Vishnu</a> and adopted the title of <i>Adivaraha</i> which is inscribed on some of his coins.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> One of the outstanding political figures of India in ninth century, he ranks with <a href=\"/wiki/Dhruva_Dharavarsha\" title=\"Dhruva Dharavarsha\">Dhruva Dharavarsha</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Dharmapala_(emperor)\" title=\"Dharmapala (emperor)\">Dharmapala</a> as a great general and empire builder.<sup id=\"cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>At its height, Bhoja's empire extended to <a href=\"/wiki/Narmada_River\" title=\"Narmada River\">Narmada River</a> in the South, <a href=\"/wiki/Sutlej\" title=\"Sutlej\">Sutlej River</a> in the northwest, and up to <a href=\"/wiki/Bengal\" title=\"Bengal\">Bengal</a> in the east. It extended over a large area from the foot of the <a href=\"/wiki/Himalayas\" title=\"Himalayas\">Himalayas</a> up to the river <a href=\"/wiki/Narmada_River\" title=\"Narmada River\">Narmada</a> and included the present district of <a href=\"/wiki/Etawah\" title=\"Etawah\">Etawah</a> in <a href=\"/wiki/Uttar_Pradesh\" title=\"Uttar Pradesh\">Uttar Pradesh</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Reign\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reign</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Military_career\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Military career</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Coins_of_Mihira_Bhoja\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Coins of Mihira Bhoja</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Notes\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Notes</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reign\">Reign</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mihira_Bhoja&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Reign\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r856303569\">@media all and (max-width:720px){.mw-parser-output .tmulti>.thumbinner{width:100%!important;max-width:none!important}.mw-parser-output .tmulti .tsingle{float:none!important;max-width:none!important;width:100%!important;text-align:center}}</style><div class=\"thumb tmulti tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:392px;max-width:392px\"><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:124px;max-width:124px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\" style=\"height:179px;overflow:hidden\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Sculptures_near_Teli_Mandir,_Gwalior_Fort.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Sculptures_near_Teli_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg/122px-Sculptures_near_Teli_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg\" width=\"122\" height=\"180\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Sculptures_near_Teli_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg/183px-Sculptures_near_Teli_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/69/Sculptures_near_Teli_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg/244px-Sculptures_near_Teli_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"660\" data-file-height=\"976\" /></a></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left;text-align:center\">Sculptures near <a href=\"/wiki/Teli_ka_Mandir\" title=\"Teli ka Mandir\">Teli ka Mandir</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Gwalior_Fort\" title=\"Gwalior Fort\">Gwalior Fort</a>.</div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:141px;max-width:141px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\" style=\"height:179px;overflow:hidden\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Gate_of_Teki_Mandir,_Gwalior_Fort.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Gate_of_Teki_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg/139px-Gate_of_Teki_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg\" width=\"139\" height=\"180\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Gate_of_Teki_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg/209px-Gate_of_Teki_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/Gate_of_Teki_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg/278px-Gate_of_Teki_Mandir%2C_Gwalior_Fort.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"3087\" data-file-height=\"4000\" /></a></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left;text-align:center\">Gate of Teli ka Mandir, Gwalior Fort.</div></div><div class=\"tsingle\" style=\"float:left;margin:1px;width:121px;max-width:121px\"><div class=\"thumbimage\" style=\"height:179px;overflow:hidden\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Teli_ka_mandir_fort_Gwalior_-_panoramio_-_Gyanendrasinghchauha%E2%80%A6_(1).jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Teli_ka_mandir_fort_Gwalior_-_panoramio_-_Gyanendrasinghchauha%E2%80%A6_%281%29.jpg/119px-Teli_ka_mandir_fort_Gwalior_-_panoramio_-_Gyanendrasinghchauha%E2%80%A6_%281%29.jpg\" width=\"119\" height=\"179\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Teli_ka_mandir_fort_Gwalior_-_panoramio_-_Gyanendrasinghchauha%E2%80%A6_%281%29.jpg/179px-Teli_ka_mandir_fort_Gwalior_-_panoramio_-_Gyanendrasinghchauha%E2%80%A6_%281%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/52/Teli_ka_mandir_fort_Gwalior_-_panoramio_-_Gyanendrasinghchauha%E2%80%A6_%281%29.jpg/238px-Teli_ka_mandir_fort_Gwalior_-_panoramio_-_Gyanendrasinghchauha%E2%80%A6_%281%29.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"332\" data-file-height=\"500\" /></a></div><div class=\"thumbcaption\" style=\"clear:left;text-align:center\"><a href=\"/wiki/Teli_ka_Mandir\" title=\"Teli ka Mandir\">Teli ka Mandir</a> is a Hindu Temple built by Mihira Bhoja.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Bajpai2006_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Bajpai2006-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup></div></div><div style=\"clear:left\"></div></div></div>\n<p>During his reign, the capital was in <a href=\"/wiki/Kannauj\" title=\"Kannauj\">Kannauj</a> (present-day <a href=\"/wiki/Uttar_Pradesh\" title=\"Uttar Pradesh\">Uttar Pradesh</a>), during his period Kannauj was referred as <a href=\"/wiki/Panchala\" title=\"Panchala\">Panchala</a>.\n</p><p>He was a bitter enemy of the <a href=\"/wiki/Arab\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Arab\">Arab</a> invaders<sup id=\"cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> who, according to an Arab chronicler, <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sulaiman_(chronicler)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Sulaiman (chronicler) (page does not exist)\">Sulaiman</a>, maintained a large army and had a fine cavalry.<sup id=\"cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The territories under his rule were prosperous and safe from robbers. His state was rich in natural resources, especially gold and silver mines.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (November 2012)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p><p>Many temples made by him still survive. Teli Mandir, near <a href=\"/wiki/Gwalior\" title=\"Gwalior\">Gwalior</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Madhya_Pradesh\" title=\"Madhya Pradesh\">Madhya Pradesh</a>, marks the presence of <a href=\"/wiki/Vishnu\" title=\"Vishnu\">Vishnu</a> on  earth. The temple's architecture, design and layout features an outstanding fusion of architectural styles: the roof resembles a Dravidian style while the decoration highlights the art of North India.\n</p><p>He was succeeded by his son <a href=\"/wiki/Mahendrapala_I\" title=\"Mahendrapala I\">Mahendrapala I</a> (c.836 - 910 CE).\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Military_career\">Military career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mihira_Bhoja&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Military career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>When Mihira Bhoja started his career reverses and defeats suffered by his father Ramabhadra had considerably lowered the prestige of the Royal <a href=\"/wiki/Gurjara_Pratihara\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Gurjara Pratihara\">Gurjara Pratihara</a> family. He invaded the <a href=\"/wiki/Pala_Empire\" title=\"Pala Empire\">Pala Empire</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Bengal\" title=\"Bengal\">Bengal</a>, but was defeated by <a href=\"/wiki/Devapala_(Pala_dynasty)\" title=\"Devapala (Pala dynasty)\">Devapala</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> He then launched a campaign to conquer the territories to the south of his empire and was successful. After Devapala's death, Bhoja defeated the <a href=\"/wiki/Pala_Empire\" title=\"Pala Empire\">Pala</a> King <a href=\"/wiki/Narayanapala\" title=\"Narayanapala\">Narayanapala</a> and the <a href=\"/wiki/Rashtrakuta\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Rashtrakuta\">Rashtrakuta</a> ruler <a href=\"/wiki/Krishna_II\" title=\"Krishna II\">Krishna II</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Sen_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Sen-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup class=\"reference\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">:<span>20\u201321</span></sup>  He gradually rebuilt the empire by conquest of territories in <a href=\"/wiki/Rajasthan\" title=\"Rajasthan\">Rajasthan</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Gujarat\" title=\"Gujarat\">Gujarat</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Madhya_Pradesh\" title=\"Madhya Pradesh\">Madhya Pradesh</a>. The <a href=\"/wiki/Chandela\" title=\"Chandela\">Chandelas</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Bundelkhand\" title=\"Bundelkhand\">Bundelkhand</a> acknowledged his suzerainty.<sup id=\"cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Besides being a conqueror, Bhoja was a great diplomat.<sup id=\"cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\nAccording to the sources (inscriptions found in Gawilor)  Mihira Bhoja defeated <a href=\"/wiki/Dharmapala\" title=\"Dharmapala\">Dharmapala</a>  the ruler of <a href=\"/wiki/Pala_Empire\" title=\"Pala Empire\">Pala Empire</a>. But defeated by his son <a href=\"/wiki/Devapala_(Pala_dynasty)\" title=\"Devapala (Pala dynasty)\">Devapala</a>. There are other sources which claims that  Mihira Bhoja defeated some of the <a href=\"/wiki/Arab\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Arab\">Arab</a>  rulers  of the northwest.<sup class=\"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">&#91;<i><a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed\" title=\"Wikipedia:Citation needed\"><span title=\"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (May 2018)\">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Coins_of_Mihira_Bhoja\">Coins of Mihira Bhoja</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mihira_Bhoja&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Coins of Mihira Bhoja\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"thumb tleft\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pratihara_bhoja.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/7d/Pratihara_bhoja.JPG/220px-Pratihara_bhoja.JPG\" width=\"220\" height=\"127\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/7d/Pratihara_bhoja.JPG/330px-Pratihara_bhoja.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/7/7d/Pratihara_bhoja.JPG/440px-Pratihara_bhoja.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"586\" data-file-height=\"337\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Pratihara_bhoja.JPG\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div><i>Adivaraha Dramma</i> coin, circa 836 - 885 CE</div></div></div>\n<p>Mihira Bhoja's epithet was <i><a href=\"/wiki/Varaha\" title=\"Varaha\">Srimad-Adivaraha</a></i> (the  fortunate primeval boar incarnation of <a href=\"/wiki/Vishnu\" title=\"Vishnu\">Vishnu</a>) and therefore there is a broad agreement amongst the scholars on the attribution of <i>adivaraha dramma</i> billon coins to him. These coins have a depiction of <i>Adivaraha</i> on the obverse.<sup id=\"cite_ref-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Notes\">Notes</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Mihira_Bhoja&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Notes\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Satish Chandra, National Council of Educational Research and Training (India) (1978). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?cd=7&amp;id=tHVDAAAAYAAJ&amp;dq=adivaraha+mihir+bhoj&amp;q=adivaraha#search_anchor\"><i>Medieval India: a textbook for classes XI-XII, Part 1</i></a>. National Council of Educational Research and Training. p.&#160;9.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Medieval+India%3A+a+textbook+for+classes+XI-XII%2C+Part+1&amp;rft.pages=9&amp;rft.pub=National+Council+of+Educational+Research+and+Training&amp;rft.date=1978&amp;rft.au=Satish+Chandra%2C+National+Council+of+Educational+Research+and+Training+%28India%29&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fcd%3D7%26id%3DtHVDAAAAYAAJ%26dq%3Dadivaraha%2Bmihir%2Bbhoj%26q%3Dadivaraha%23search_anchor&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AMihira+Bhoja\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-&quot;&quot;RSC_207&quot;_2-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Radhey Shyam Chaurasia (2002). <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=cWmsQQ2smXIC&amp;pg=PA207&amp;dq\"><i>History of Ancient India: Earliest Times to 1000 A. D.</i></a> Atlantic Publishers &amp; Distributors. p.&#160;207. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-81-269-0027-5\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-81-269-0027-5\">978-81-269-0027-5</a>. <q>He was undoubtedly one of the outstanding political figures of India in ninth century and ranks with Dhruva and Dharmapala as a great general and empire builder.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.bti